@<Head@>@(@, Coupling from the past (CFTP)@)

@<Subsection@>@(Trouble with MCMC@)
MCMC suffers from one great problem, viz, choice of the
length of the chain. Unless we have good ways to check convergence the
distribution that we get may be a poor approximation to the target
distribution. One way to remedy this is by using CFTP. The basic idea is
as follows.

<p>Run more than one version of the chain in parallel. Based on
their relative
behaviour decide when to stop.
Thus, instead of running the chain for a
prespecified length, here we run it until a stopping time.
This is again our familiar sequential
sampling idea. 


@<Subsection@>@(MC from another perspective@)
Propp-Wilson algorithm works only for finite sample space. There are
generalisations for infinite cases, that we shall not go into. 
A MC on a
finite sample space S is essentially determined by a transition
matrix. (We do not care about the initial distribution here.)
This is the traditional view of MC. Here we shall introduce
another approach: random map view. 

<p>In this view we have a bunch of maps from S to S. Call these as

@<Disp@>@(f<sub>1</sub>,...,f<sub>N</sub>,@)

and attach probabilities 

@<Disp@>@(p<sub>1</sub>,...,p<sub>N</sub>@)

to them. p<sub>i</sub>'s add up to 1. Now, our
step is made as follows. Suppose that we are at x. Pick one of the N maps
at random, say, f<sub>i</sub> with probability p@<sub@>@(i@).
Then move to f<sub>i</sub>(x). 

<p>
@<Example@>@( Consider the simple symmetric random walk modulo 7.
